        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1772374794" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17453324661576359527">3.5 stars.<br/><br/>I loved revisiting the world of Vianne and Anouk whose story we were so richly introduced to in Chocolat. I only found out a few years ago that there was a sequel to Chocolat and it’s been on my list of things to read for quite a while.<br/><br/>Four years have passed since the events in the chocolaterie. Anouk is now eleven and she has a sister, Rosette. Vianne is not quite herself. Events over the last few years have shaken her up quite a bit and she’s afraid to use even the tiniest piece of m</span>
  <span id="freeText17453324661576359527" style="display:none">3.5 stars.<br /><br />I loved revisiting the world of Vianne and Anouk whose story we were so richly introduced to in Chocolat. I only found out a few years ago that there was a sequel to Chocolat and it’s been on my list of things to read for quite a while.<br /><br />Four years have passed since the events in the chocolaterie. Anouk is now eleven and she has a sister, Rosette. Vianne is not quite herself. Events over the last few years have shaken her up quite a bit and she’s afraid to use even the tiniest piece of magic. Vianne might pretend that she’s happy to settle in Paris and not live the life she’s supposed to.<br /><br />But when Zozie, a fun, daring, breath of fresh air comes into their life, everything changes. Of course Zozie isn’t quite who she seems. <br /><br />I don’t want to give any more away but I really enjoyed this novel and would definitely recommend it for fans of Chocolat. You do need to have read the first book or at least have watched the movie before reading this one.</span>
